04060nam a22007215i 9780271071633DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20211995pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710716337 a10.1515/97802710716332doi  a(DE-B1597)584070  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aJC578b.K56 1995 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a320/.01/12201 aKingwell, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Civil Tongue :bJustice, Dialogue, and the Politics of Pluralism /cMark Kingwell. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tPart One -- t1. Interpretation, Dialogue, and the Just Citizen -- t2. A First Look at Civility -- tPart Two -- t3. Constrained Liberal Dialogue -- t4. Tradition and Translation -- t5. Justice and Communicative Action -- tPart Three -- t6. Justice as Civility -- t7. The Limits of Civility -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is about a widely shared desire: the desire among citizens for a vibrant and effective social discourse of legitimation. It therefore begins with the conviction that what political philosophy can provide citizens is not further theories of the good life but instead directions for talking about how to justify the choices they make-or, in brief, ";just talking.";As part of the general trend away from the aridity of Kantian universalism in political philosophy, thinkers as diverse as Bruce Ackerman, Jürgen Habermas, Alasdair MacIntyre, and Richard Rorty have taken a ";dialogic turn"; that seeks to understand the determination of principles of justice as a cooperative task, achieved in some kind of social dialogue among real citizens. In one way or another, however, each of these different variations on the dialogic model fail to provide fully satisfactory answers, Mark Kingwell shows. Drawing on their strengths, he presents another model he calls ";justice as civility,"; which makes original use of the popular literature on etiquette and work in sociolinguistics to develop a more adequate theory of dialogic justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aCourtesy. 0aCourtoisie. 0aCultural pluralism. 0aDialogue. 0aEtiquette. 0aJustice. 0aPluralisme. 0aSavoir-vivre. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271071633zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271071633423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271071633.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK